'''Bonifaty Mikhailovich Kedrov''' ({{lang-ru|ÐÐ¾Ð½Ð¸ÑÐ°ÌÑÐ¸Ð¹ ÐÐ¸Ñ Ð°ÌÐ¹Ð»Ð¾Ð²Ð¸Ñ ÐÐµÌÐ´ÑÐ¾Ð²}}) ({{OldStyleDate|10 December|1903|27 November}}, [[Yaroslavl]] â 10 September 1985, Moscow) was a notable [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] researcher, [[philosopher]], [[logician]], [[chemist]] and [[psychologist]]. He joined the [[Bolsheviks]] in 1918.
Kedrov had a [[Doktor nauk|Doctor]] of Philosophy degree and specialized in philosophical questions of the natural sciences. He was a member of the [[Soviet Academy of Sciences]] since 1966,<ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uv1zv4FZhFUC|title = Memoirs of Nikita Khrushchev|last = Khrushchev|first = Nikita Sergeevich|last2 = Khrushchev|first2 = Serge_|date = 2006-01-01|publisher = Penn State Press|isbn = 0271028610|language = en}}</ref> author of over one thousand publications.
Kedrov was (since 1963) member of the [[International Academy of the History of Science]] and a number of other institutions. Kedrov was one of the initiators and the first editor-in-chief of ''[[Problems of philosophy (magazine)|Problems of philosophy]]'' (Voprosy filosofii) a leading Soviet journal of philosophy, from 1947 to 1949.<ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=l1Ha_opwB68C|title = Stalin's Great Science: The Times and Adventures of Soviet Physicists|last = Kozhevnikov|first = A. B.|date = 2004-01-01|publisher = Imperial College Press|isbn = 9781860944192|language = en}}</ref>
