'''Jaideva Singh''' (19 September 1893 {{#tag:ref|Some sources state 1896<ref>{{cite book|last=Menon|first=Rekha|title=Cultural Profiles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OmtDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=August 4, 2013|year=1961|publisher=Inter-National Cultural Centre}}</ref>|group="nb"}} in [[Shoratgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of the Indian Musicological Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JskJAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=August 4, 2013|year=1986|publisher=Indian Musicological Society}}</ref> â 27 May 1986 in <ref name="Misra2001">{{cite book|last=Misra|first=Susheela|title=Among contemporary musicians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GL8GAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=August 4, 2013|date=1 January 2001|publisher=Harman Pub. House|page=232}}</ref> [[Banaras]]) was an Indian [[musicologist]] and [[philosopher]]. He played a key role in the development of [[All India Radio]] where he was chief producer.<ref name="Roy2004">{{cite book|last=Roy|first=Ashok|title=Music makers: living legends of Indian classical music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BpGfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=February 2, 2004|publisher=Rupa & Co.}}</ref><ref name=hin09>{{cite news |title=Finding her own voice|author=Gowri Ramnarayan |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2009/04/17/stories/2009041751100100.htm |publisher=The Hindu |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> He was influenced by the Indian [[musicologist]] [[Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande]].<ref name="University2005">{{cite book|last=Bakhle|first=Janaki|title=Two Men and Music: Nationalism in the Making of an Indian Classical Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o8Qs7TD4n4sC&pg=PA258|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=17 September 2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-534731-9|page=258}}</ref>

Singh was a renowned scholar in the [[Kashmir Saivism]] school of [[Indian philosophy]],<ref name="Rastogi1987">{{cite book|last=Rastogi|first=Navjivan|title=Introduction to the TantrÄloka: a study in structure|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3559AAAAMAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2013|year=1987|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|page=14}}</ref><ref name="Rastogi1979">{{cite book|last=Rastogi|first=Navjivan|title=The krama tantricism of Kashmir: historical and general sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qgsYAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=1 January 1979|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass}}</ref> a subject he studied for many years with [[Swami Lakshman Joo]] in [[Kashmir]]. He prepared and published first-ever English and Hindi translations of a number of Shaivite scriptures.<ref>{{cite book|title=Saints and Sages of Kashmir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_kb815NoRRoC&pg=PA297|accessdate=August 4, 2013|date=1 January 2004|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-7648-576-0|page=297}}</ref> Singh was appointed as the Chairman of the [[Uttar Pradesh Sangeet Natak Akademi]] in 1973.  He was awarded the [[Padma Bhushan]] in 1974 for his contribution to music.

