A {{Nihongo|'''kaisandÅ'''|éå±±å |kaisan-dÅ}}, also termed the '''Founder's Hall''', is a temple structure in a Japanese [[Buddhist]] [[monastery]] complex or other temple where an image (or images) of the founding [[abbot]] and other significant teachers and [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] ancestors are kept,<ref>Kinoshita, 58</ref> along with a memorial slab (J. [[ihai]]). Sometimes also referred to as the Patriarch Hall (J. ''soshido'') or Reflection Hall (J. ''Eishitsu''), this building holds [[funeral|memorial service]]s yearly on the anniversary of the death of the founding abbot.<ref name="baroni">Baroni, 95</ref>

The largest Founder's Hall in Japan is the Goei-dÅ (å¾¡å½±å ) in front of the [[Hongan-ji|Higashi Hongwanji]] (Hongan-ji) Temple in [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]], one of two head temples of the [[JÅdo ShinshÅ«]] sect of Buddhism.

